{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17537107","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17537107"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:13:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:13:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15904"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15904"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.37,0.13,0.22,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8595"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104999"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8595"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15904"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87387"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1315"},{"type":"tags","id":"4119"},{"type":"tags","id":"4543"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11109"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20598"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35220"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35221"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104999","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104999"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for follow-up eight weeks after an uncomplicated vasectomy. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He estimates he has had 15 ejaculations since the procedure and wants to know if he can stop using condoms with his partner.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The surgical sites are well-healed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arrange semen analysis now","Continue barrier contraception and review in four weeks","Advise he is safe to cease barrier contraception","Refer for semen analysis now and in six weeks","Arrange semen analysis at six months"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents for post-vasectomy follow-up to determine if the procedure has been effective. The timing and number of ejaculations are both insufficient to reliably confirm sterility at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe should be advised to \u003Cstrong\u003Econtinue barrier contraception and review in four weeks\u003C/strong\u003E. Whilst there is differing advice, most Australian guidelines recommend waiting at least 12 weeks and having at least 20 ejaculations before performing semen analysis to confirm sterility. This allows sufficient time for residual sperm to be cleared from the reproductive tract.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArranging semen analysis now\u003C/strong\u003E would be premature at eight weeks post-procedure, as there is a high likelihood of finding residual sperm which would necessitate repeat testing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdvising that he is safe to cease barrier contraception\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Healing of the surgical sites does not correlate with achievement of sterility and pregnancy can still occur until azoospermia is confirmed so formal testing is advised.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERefer for semen analysis now and in six weeks\u003C/strong\u003E would be unnecessary. Testing now would not meet the minimum 12-week waiting period. Australian guidelines do not recommend repeat testing if the initial semen analysis is satisfactory, so a second test is not recommended. Additionally, the patient has not yet achieved 20 ejaculations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArranging semen analysis at six months\u003C/strong\u003E would delay confirmation of sterility unnecessarily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPost-vasectomy testing is crucial to confirm the success of the procedure. About 1 in 100 men who have had a vasectomy will still have sperm in their semen even months after the procedure, highlighting the importance of proper follow-up testing before discontinuing other forms of contraception.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Post-vasectomy semen analysis should be performed at least 12 weeks after the procedure and after at least 20 ejaculations.","A negative semen analysis is required to confirm sterility after vasectomy.","Alternative contraception must be used until azoospermia is confirmed with semen analysis."],"references":["Badrakumar C, Gogoi NK, Sundaram SK. Semen analysis after vasectomy: when and how many? BJU Int. 2000 Sep;86(4):479-81. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10971276/","Griffin T, Tooher R, Nowakowski K, Lloyd M, Maddern G. How little is enough? The evidence for post-vasectomy testing. Journal of Urology [Internet]. 2005 Jul 1;174(1):29\u201336. Available at: https://doi.org/10.1097/01.ju.0000161595.82642.fc"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87387"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15904"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87387"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-06T13:45:39+09:30","